\b0 \cf0 \
1\super st\nosupersub  Speech    (Case Flow)\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0
\cf0 \ul \ulc0 First Affirmative Constructive\ulnone \'971AC\
7 minutes (All times are maximum.)\
Duty: To present the Affirmative\'92s Prima Facie Case for the Resolution.\
\
Topicality\
Significant Harm\'97Argument 1\
Inherency\'97Argument 2\
Affirmative Plan\
Solvency\'97Argument 3\
\
\
At the end of this speech you will be involved in a cross examination by the person on the negative who will be the second negative speaker.  2 minutes.\
\
No arguments can be made in cross-examination by the questioner:(2N Speaker).  You can only ask questions.  The affirmative speaker must try to answer all questions honestly.  At worse say, I don\'92t know the answer to that question.\
\
2\super nd\nosupersub  Speech  (Case Flow)\
\ul First Negative Constructive\ulnone \'971NC\
4 minutes\
Duty: To present Two or Three refutation responses to 2 of the affirmatives arguments.   (Burden of Refutation)\
\
(Four steps to refute an argument.)\
\
1.You should tell us what argument you will be refuting, by using the signposts of the affirmative and repeating what you believe their claim was. (is).\
\
2.Then you should signpost your first response, and tell us your refutation claim. \
\
3. Then support with analysis and/or evidence.\
\
4. Finally, tell us what is the impact of winning your response.  (What does it do to  the affirmative\'92s argument.)\
\
After your first refutation argument, you should present your second refutation argument by going to step #2 above.  \
Then you should go to the second affirmative argument by using the four-step approach starting with step one. \
\
At the end of this speech you will be involved in a cross-examination by the person on the affirmative who did the first affirmative speech.  2 minutes\
3\super rd\nosupersub  Speech  (Case Flow)\
\ul Second Affirmative Constructive\ulnone \'971AC\
4 minutes\
Duty: To Rejoined (rebuild) the two arguments of the affirmative that have been refuted by the first negative.  (Burden of rejoinder)  And then you should claim victory on the one affirmative argument that was not refuted by the first negative.\
\
(Steps to rejoined)\
\
1. You should reintroduce the argument to us.  Use the signpost, the claim and give us a brief synopsis of what was proven in the original argument.\
\
2.You should tell us what the first refutation argument is.\
\
3. You should refute the refutation argument. (Rejoined) Tell us what is wrong with the refutation argument and why we should believe your argument.\
\
4. Support your rejoinder with analysis and/or evidence.\
\
5. Finally, tell us what is the impact of winning your response.\
\
Next, you address the second refutation argument by repeating the above steps starting with #2.\
\
Then you should go to the second affirmative argument that was refuted by the first negative and address starting with Step one.\
\
Lastly, Reintroduce the argument that was not refuted.  Tell us that the argument was not refuted and that at the end of the debate the judges know that the affirmative will win that particular issue.   (Remember the negative cannot argue this argument in rebuttals because it would be a new argument.)\
\
At the end of this speech you will be involved in a cross-examination by the person on the negative who was be the first negative speaker.  2 minutes.\
\
\
\
